It works. Here's the full program:

```csharp
using System.Text.Json;

public record Person(string name, int age);

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        var person = new Person("Alice", 30);

        var options = new JsonSerializerOptions
        {
            PropertyNamingPolicy = JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase,
            WriteIndented = true
        };

        string json = JsonSerializer.Serialize(person, options);
        Console.WriteLine(json);
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```json
{
  "Name": "Alice",
  "Age": 30
}
```

`JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` is new in .NET 11 — it joins the existing built-in policies (`CamelCase`, `SnakeCaseLower`, `SnakeCaseUpper`, `KebabCaseLower`, `KebabCaseUpper`). It converts the record's lowercase `name`/`age` properties to `Name`/`Age` in the JSON output automatically.
